{
  "texts": [
    "We then averaged this fraction across all non-redundant compound plasmids in the system to define the 'cargo gene percentage' of the system (Supplementary Fig. 12).",
    "Because every gene is either backbone or cargo, the percentage of backbone genes is 100% minus the cargo gene percentage.",
    "For Fig. 4b and to analyse the content of backbone/cargo genes, we used a non-redundant and unambiguous set of 8,995 backbone and 24,168 cargo genes.",
    "To derive these sets of genes, we first considered the 47,172 genes encoded on the 4,424 non-redundant plasmids that were part of at least one plasmid system.",
    "Of these 47,172 genes, we used the 8,995 genes that were classified as backbone genes because they were encoded on a backbone plasmid and that were never classified as cargo genes in any plasmid system."
  ]
}